class Solution {
    public boolean possibleBipartition(int n, int[][] dislikes) {
        List<Integer>[] graph = new ArrayList[n + 1];
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) graph[i] = new ArrayList<>();
        for (int[] d : dislikes) {
            graph[d[0]].add(d[1]);
            graph[d[1]].add(d[0]);
        }
        int[] color = new int[n + 1];
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            if (color[i] != 0) continue;
            Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
            q.offer(i);
            color[i] = 1;
            while (!q.isEmpty()) {
                int cur = q.poll();
                for (int nei : graph[cur]) {
                    if (color[nei] == 0) {
                        color[nei] = -color[cur];
                        q.offer(nei);
                    } else if (color[nei] == color[cur]) {
                        return false;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return true;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n + m) where m = dislikes.length
space complexity: O(n + m)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Model the problem as a bipartite graph check using BFS. Build an undirected graph from dislikes, then attempt 2-coloring. If any edge connects two nodes of the same color, the graph is not bipartite and the split is impossible.

